The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Monday, March 22, 2004 				 NTPC plugs for venture with Bharat Heavy Electricals
 SRINJOY SHARMA Energy bond 																								New Delhi, March 21: National Thermal Power Corporation (NTPC) and Bharat Heavy Electricals Ltd (Bhel) are forming a joint venture that will undertake engineering, procurement and construction.																								The firm  in which the two state-owned companies plan to hold an equal stake  will be established in the first quarter (April-June) of 2004-05.																								The governing boards of the two state-run firms have approved the plan to form the joint venture. 																								Sources said the power generation firm is also planning to set up two separate subsidiaries that will trade in power and undertake electricity distribution.																								The formalities are expected to be completed by April and the new company, which will comprise officials from both companies, is likely to be operational by the first week of May, sources said. NTPC is holding talks with several state-run firms to form joint venture units.																								The new joint venture with Bhel will synergise the operations of both the state-run firms, analysts said. While Bhel will offer manufacturing and services, NTPC will be able to provide technical expertise, he said.																								Company officials said the firm plans to widen its operations from a mere power generation company to one that has diversified interests through the joint venture route.																								NTPC, which is expected to raise around Rs 920 crore ($200 million) through the issue of seven-year bonds, already has joint venture units formed with Steel Authority of India (SAIL), BSES and ABB Alstom.																								It has also signed a MoU with Indian Railways to set up power projects. I has also has an agreement with Indian Oil to set up power plants powered by petroleum.																								Company official said proceeds from NTPC issue will be used for capital expenditure designed to raise its electricity generation facilities.																								The bonds will be the second debt issue to be offered this year following Industrial Development Bank of Indias $300 million, five-year bond offering.Tata Power project																								PTI adds: Tata Power, the countrys largest private power producer, would soon hold discussions with Uttar Pradesh government about setting up a 1000-MW thermal power project estimated to cost at around Rs 4,000 crore.																								We (Tata Power) have been invited by Uttar Pradesh government recently for a dialogue over the proposed mega power project, said Anil Sardana, chief executive, North Delhi Power, Tatas power distribution arm. 
